From 24397c9d764b2a10f0fb30f5f704ab249cac16ab Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 2026 06:38:10 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] fix(store-bypass): close VendorIngestionDesk and
 CleansingView bypasses (Phase 2)
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

VendorIngestionDesk.tsx:
- Was importing VENDORS directly from lib/mockData/misc, bypassing
  coreStore entirely. A heal action updating a vendor's credentials/
  status via setVendors would never be reflected here, even though
  VendorPortal.tsx (the parent) already reads vendors from the store
  for VendorGateways — it just never threaded the prop down.
- Added vendors to VendorIngestionDeskProps; resolvePortalConfig now
  takes vendors as a parameter instead of reading the module-level
  import. VendorPortal.tsx now passes vendors={vendors}, matching how
  every other store value already flows to this component.
- Added a regression test proving default credentials are driven by
  the vendors prop, not a static import.

CleansingView.tsx:
- entries was seeded via a one-shot useState(() => generateMockEntries
  (catalogSkus)) initializer, so it never re-derived if catalogSkus
  changed after mount (e.g. a heal action correcting a SKU that a
  cleansing entry should now match).
- A naive useMemo swap would have been worse: entries also holds
  in-progress user work (manual mapping, quarantine, auto-map
  promotions), which a pure recompute would silently discard.
- Fix: baselineEntries is now a useMemo keyed on catalogSkus; a sync
  useEffect merges the fresh baseline in per-entry, but preserves any
  entry the user has already touched (mapped, quarantined, or
  auto-map-promoted — all three now stamp reviewedAt as the signal).
- Added a regression test proving both halves: a catalog change flips
  a previously-unmatched entry once the matching SKU exists, while a
  separately-quarantined entry survives the same resync untouched.

Verified: tsc --noEmit clean, full vitest suite green (84 files /
389 tests, 0 regressions).
